Riya, a student, wants to sell her old mobile phone through an online ad. A short while later, she got a message from a "buyer" who showed interest and agreed to make an instant UPI payment. The buyer sent her a QR code and told her to scan it to “receive” the money. Riya scanned the code and entered her UPI pin after following the instructions. Her account was debited to the tune of ₹10,000 instead of crediting any money.
Typically, these steps are followed in this fraud case.
The fraudster acts as a buyer or customer and then contacts the victim.
They build confidence and establish urgency (e.g., offer of quick payment).
They send a requested payment or a QR code.
The victim is duped into entering their UPI PIN.
The scam artist obtains money immediately.

Section B
College students and online vendors are often targeted due to their constant use of digital platforms and ignorance of UPI security protocols. 
Among the consequences are financial loss, psychological stress, and loss of trust in online systems. As digital transactions are usually instantaneous and cannot be undone, victims may also have a tough time getting back their money.
College students in India.
1. Whatever be the situation, do not share your UPI PIN with anyone including bank workers. 
Remember that a QR code is scanned to pay and not to receive money.
Before approving any payment requests, check them. 
Don't open suspicious attachments or click on untrusted links.
Enable two-factor authentication for all important accounts.
Create Powerful & Unique Password for All Sites.
2. Never make online financial transactions on public Wi-Fi.
Frequently verify your banking statements for transactions that seem off.
Only install apps from official app stores. 
Refrain from sharing sensitive information (OTP, Aadhaar, bank details) over calls or messages.
* UPI and Financial Security Guidelines
Ensure the recipient's UPI ID is correct before sending money.
Never enter your UPI PIN to "receive" anything.
Section C: Introspection (100–150 words)
The thing that shocked me the most during my research on this subject was how easy tricks, like sending a QR code, can result in large financial losses. Instead of using cutting-edge technology, many scams take advantage of people's ignorance and sense of urgency. I discovered that even well-educated users, such as college students, are susceptible to falling for these kinds of scams.
Being more cautious before approving any online transaction is one habit I will personally break. In the past, I didn't always verify payment requests or recognize the distinction between sending and receiving money through UPI. I will now carefully check every transaction detail and make sure I am making a payment before entering my UPI PIN. This knowledge can help avoid needless financial risks.

